Results of this due diligence will be contained in credit applications to establish or maintain TFP 
credit lines for participating banks. Information derived from the TA will benefit the banks by 
identifying where they lack capacity, and it will enable ADB to provide capacity development to 
banks and specific banking systems in DMCs.  

12.  The periodic bank monitoring assessments (annual reviews) are based on the principle 
of repeat engagement over the medium and long term for effective capacity building. ADB will 
conduct yearly financial assessments (and/or quarterly covenant reviews). As ADB assumes 
risk  on  the  vast  majority  of  these  banks  through  the  TFP,  ongoing  assessments  (annual 
reviews) and monitoring are required to ensure ADB continues to assume reasonable risks.  

13.  The TA activities will include the following:   

(i)  work with individual banks to acquire financial data;  
(ii)  analyze the financial information through financial, ratio, gap, and other analyses; 
(iii)  conduct due diligence on banks through (a) holding meetings with banks; (b) 
assessing corporate governance, anti-money-laundering policies, and 
management capabilities; and (c) asking the banks questions related to financial 
analysis; 
(iv)  assess the trade finance operations capacity for selected banks and make 
recommendations for improvement; 
(v)  draft credit applications to be submitted to the TFP;  
(vi)  conduct a banking sector analysis for each DMC; 
(vii)  conduct signing ceremonies with new partner banks; and 
(viii)  deliver trade finance training. 

b.  Knowledge Dissemination and Training Seminars 

14.  Information  on  where  individual  banks  lack  finance  and  technical  capacity  will  be 
conveyed directly to those banks on a confidential basis. In addition, the TA proposes to 
disseminate more general information about trade finance operations and provide trade finance 
training to a larger audience within DMCs through in-country seminars to which DMC banks, 
exporters, government officials, and international banks may be invited if appropriate.  

15.  ADB plans to conduct a total of two seminars over the course of the TA. The knowledge 
dissemination and/or training seminar could cover the following areas: 

(i)  key concepts and processes in trade finance; 
(ii)  benefits to banks from trade finance services; 
(iii)  essentials to develop and market trade finance products and services; 
(iv)  payment and risk categories; 
(v)  risk analysis of trade finance products; 
(vi)  fundamentals of documentary credits; 
(vii)  types of letter of credit and standby credit; 
(viii)  types of bonds and guarantees; and  
(ix)  receivables and supply chain financing. 


5  The TA will coordinate with the TFP to target banks where there is market demand for capacity development.

